 edition addresses adjustments throughout the industry wrought by broadband delivered television such as Netflix, YouTube, and cross-platform initiatives like TV Everywhere, as well as how technologies such as tablets and smartphones have changed how and where we view. Lotz begins to deconstruct the future of different kinds of television—exploring how “prized content,” live television sports and contests, and linear viewing may all be “television,” but very different types of television for both viewers and producers.Through interviews with those working in the industry, surveys of trade publications, and consideration of an extensive array of popular shows, Lotz takes us behind the screen to explore what is changing, why it is changing, and why the changes matter.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aTelevision broadcastingxTechnological innovations. 0aTelevision broadcastingzUnited States. 0aTelevision broadcasting. 0aTelevisionxTechnological innovations. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Television / History & Criticism.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9781479890392.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781479890392423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781479890392/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles